With us, literary productioris belong indeed mostly to one or other main class, and so far are composed under condi- tions which prescribe the form ε though even here constantly new varieties are invented: but both in style and subject-matter, the aim of all great writers is to be original. The Roman literature on the other hand was mainly formed on Greek models ; and to adhere to those models closely, to be constantly reminding the readers of them, to imitate them much in the treatment, in the phraseology‚ and even in the incident, was inevitable to the Latin poets3 or, rather, it was one of the very things they pro- posed to do in writing1. Vergil’s style, indeed, is completely his own, and entirely unlike Homer’s, as is plain from what has been said; his main purpose and subject are entirely his own, and truly Roman ; he borrows where he does borrow (and that from Ennius, Cyclic poets‚ Greek tragedians, and many others besides Homer) always to suit his own purpose, and not in a servile mannen and he invariably remains master of his materials‚ and stamps his own mark indelibly upon them.

But to understand Vergil, it is clearly necessary to grasp the conditions under which he worked3 and nothing can be a greater mistake than to feel surprise at the extent to which he was indebted to his predecessors in the poetic art.
